Step-by-step execution of the modified simulation
Grid creation and initialization
The script allocates:

energy: a GRID_SIZE √ó GRID_SIZE floating array initialized to zeros using numpy.zeros, which returns a new array ‚Äúfilled with zeros.‚Äù
3
state: an integer grid initialized to zeros (EMPTY everywhere)
The center cell is seeded with:

energy[center, center] = RADIATION_START
state[center, center] = HELIUM
Per-timestep update structure
Each timestep creates:

new_energy = energy.copy()
new_state = state.copy()
NumPy documents ndarray.copy() as the preferred method for making a copy (i.e., changes to the copy do not change the original).
4

The timestep is computed in two conceptual phases (exactly as in your script):

Phase one: per-cell state-dependent energy/states
For each interior cell (i, j) (the border is intentionally skipped):

If state is EMPTY or SHELL (new law), then if the old energy e meets the helium threshold, the cell becomes HELIUM.
If state is HELIUM: energy decays and if e ‚â• COLLAPSE_THRESHOLD, the cell becomes CORE.
If state is CORE: energy decays faster and the core injects energy (EMN_PUSH) into its 8-neighborhood.
If state is SHELL: (if still SHELL after Phase one‚Äôs transitions) energy decays slowly.
This phase is what creates a heat-and-ignite cycle: energy injection creates HELIUM, and HELIUM can collapse into CORE.

Phase two: shell assignment near cores
After Phase one, any non-core cell with energy in the ‚Äúshell window‚Äù (HELIUM_THRESHOLD ‚â§ e < COLLAPSE_THRESHOLD) becomes SHELL if it is adjacent to a CORE (adjacency is checked against the previous state, so shell assignment has a one-step latency around new cores).

Animation generation
The animation renders the state grid only (imshow(frames[t])). FuncAnimation repeatedly calls the update function to change the displayed image.
5

The MP4 file is written using Animation.save, which draws every frame to the target file using the chosen writer.
7

