Conclusions grounded in logic and observed output
With only two necessary modifications‚Äî(a) the SHELL‚ÜíHELIUM ignition law and (b) MP4 saving instead of interactive display‚Äîthe simulation exhibits the full set of requested phenomena:

Collapse formation is immediate at the seed because initial energy exceeds the collapse threshold.
Core appearance is not only present but expansive: the simulation generates a coherent outward collapse wave that ultimately fills the entire updatable interior region with cores.
Recursive shell formation is observed as a continuing boundary-layer phenomenon: shells appear at successively larger radii over time (confirmed by both the video frames and the shell-arrival-time map).
Outward propagation beyond radius = 1 is clearly present: shell radius first exceeds 1 at step 6 and reaches radius 49 before the interior saturates into cores.
The run also shows a distinctive late-stage behavior: once the collapse front reaches the maximal interior radius permitted by the boundary-skipping loops, SHELL and HELIUM states vanish and the lattice becomes almost entirely CORE (with the untouched border remaining EMPTY).
